description:
Some Indian airlines have cancelled flights because of massive ash plumes from an Ethiopian volcano.  
The Hayli Gubbi volcano sent smoke and ash 14 kilometres high on Sunday, its first eruption in recorded history. 
Air India cancelled 11 flights to make precautionary checks on aircraft, that had flown near the volcano.
Akasa Air scrapped some flights to Middle East destinations including Jeddah, Kuwait, and Abu Dhabi.

Juliet Biggs is a Professor of Earth Science and Co-Director of The Centre for the Observation and Modelling of Earthquakes Volcanoes and Tectonics.
She says nearby activity that has built up over the years is likely to have caused the volcano to errupt at such a velocity.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The Taiwanese premier has ruled out the possibility of reunification with mainland China.
Cho Jung-tai said a “return” is not an option. 
His remarks came hours after Chinese President Xi Jinping mentioned the issue in a phone call with the US President Donald Trump. 

Taiwan's government has repeatedly rejected what it considers, Beijing's attempts to weaken its sovereignty. 
Earlier this month, Taiwan became the center of a diplomatic dispute between Beijing and Tokyo. 
That's after Japan's new Prime Minister Sanae Takaichi hinted that her country could intervene militarily if China attacked the self-governed island.
Her remarks provoked a furious response from Beijing. 
It suspended seafood imports from Japan and advised its citizens not to travel there. 

Al Jazeera’s Katrina Yu is in Tianjin, China with more on the remarks from the Taiwanese Premier.

Wen-Ti Sung is a specialist on China-Taiwan relations from the Atlantic Council's Global China Hub. 

Subscribe to our channel: ht
title: Taiwanese Premier Cho Jung-tai says 'return' to China 'is not an option'

description:

The war in Sudan has created the world’s largest humanitarian crisis.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Black Friday, the busiest shopping day of the year in the US, is just days away. 
Traditionally marking the start of the holiday shopping season, it follows Thanksgiving and sees millions of Americans head to stores or shop online. 
Retailers rely heavily on this period to bolster annual profits, with experts predicting as many as 187 million shoppers between Thursday and Monday—three million more than last year. 
Categories such as toys and jewellery remain critical for retailers during this time, while events like Cyber Monday extend sales into the following week.
This year, however, concerns over inflation, rising healthcare costs, and recession fears are altering consumer behaviour. 
Many Americans are expected to prioritise necessities over large purchases, while trade tariffs and fluctuating economic policies add to uncertainties. 
Despite these challenges, analysts suggest the economy remains relatively stable. Credit card spending is likely to increase, leaving some consumers
title: Black Friday looms as Americans prioritise essentials over big retail spending

Trump issued the decree on Monday as Washington intensified its crackdown on Israel’s foes in the region.
The decree accused Muslim Brotherhood leaders in Jordan of providing “material support” to Hamas and the Lebanese branch of the group – known as al-Jamaa al-Islamiya – of siding with Hamas and Hezbollah in their war with Israel.
It also claimed that an Egyptian Muslim Brotherhood leader “called for violent attacks against United States partners and interests” during Israel’s war on Gaza. But it was not clear what the White House was referring to. The Muslim Brotherhood has been banned in Egypt and mostly driven underground.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
During a UN Security Council meeting on the situation in the occupied Palestinian territories, members urged Israel to honour its ceasefire commitments by facilitating the entry of aid into Gaza. 
Calls were made to open additional border crossings and grant greater access to humanitarian workers, as delays continue to hinder relief efforts in the besieged enclave. 
The UN reports that 1.5 million people in Gaza urgently require shelter as winter approaches, with aid deliveries slowed by closed crossings and congested routes.
UN officials emphasised the urgent need for shelter materials and essential supplies, while highlighting the limited leverage the organisation has to enforce the ceasefire terms. 
Despite ongoing appeals, progress on opening crossings remains stagnant. 
The humanitarian crisis continues to escalate, with international pressure mounting for immediate action.

Al Jazeera’s Gabriel Elizondo reports from the United Nations.
